In this article, the author discusses the importance of remembering and honoring the victims of the Holocaust. They emphasize the need to give a voice to the millions of Jews, Roma, Sinti, Slavs, disabled persons, LGBTQ+ individuals, and political dissidents who were systematically killed by the Nazis and their collaborators. The author reflects on their personal connection to the Holocaust, having learned about it from their father and visiting the Dachau concentration camp with their family. They highlight the urgency of preserving the stories of survivors as their numbers dwindle. The author also emphasizes the moral obligation to combat hate and antisemitism, both at home and globally. They stress the importance of accurately teaching about the Holocaust and opposing attempts to deny or revise history. The article concludes by calling for justice for survivors and ensuring they have the necessary support and services. The author encourages a commitment to creating a better future and upholding the values of justice, equality, and diversity.